@@eThe Eccentric Woodland -- As Kowloon Sees It@@N

@@gJade Magistracy, Midgaard Frontier Analysis@@N

The Eccentric Woodland lies south of Midgaard's gates -- the opposite
direction from Kowloon, on the far side of a city we reach only
through four hundred miles of forest. By any measure, it is
@@dirrelevant to our trade, defense, and daily operations@@N.

The Jade Magistracy files it anyway. Midgaard's failures instruct.

Travelers leaving the Southern Wild Gate expect conventional frontier.
Instead, the Woodland offers @@rinconsistency@@N: clearings pastoral by
day and predatory by dusk, paths that move between visits, isolated
halls under their own ritual authority. The Courier Lantern Office
reads these reports and concludes: @@ythis is what unmaintained
jurisdiction looks like@@N.

When the Lantern Reforms tried to standardize southern routes, clerks
entered "Eccentric Woodland" as a registry label -- @@ya ledger
category admitting they could not govern the territory it named@@N.
Kowloon does not name territory it cannot administer. We mark it
@@rcrimson@@N and post warnings at the relevant gate.

Four forces contest the interior: @@gPath Wardens@@N selling navigation,
@@dRitual Houses@@N legitimating rank through ceremony, @@rPredator Bands@@N
mimicking ritual to extract compliance, and @@ySurvivor Clusters@@N
bartering in clearings. None controls the whole. The Wardens of Iron
recognize this from Coppersalt Bay's outer island chains -- contested
space where power is local and theatrical. The difference: Kowloon
@@ydoes not pretend to govern its ungovernable edges@@N. Midgaard does.

The Woodland shows what happens when @@yorder as infrastructure@@N is
applied only at boundaries. Roads no longer return to watched squares.
Registry systems lose force where witnesses are scarce. The Courier
Lantern Office translates this: @@ea lantern you cannot maintain is
a promise you should not make@@N.

Midgaard's response is bureaucratic: clean gate records, classify
incidents as variance, maintain plausible governance at the edge. Our
own @@dIron Gate@@N faces similar frontier pressure. The difference is
doctrine. We do not classify the ungovernable as variance. We call it
@@rthreat@@N, assign it a color, and maintain the gate.

The Eccentric Woodland is Midgaard's problem. It reminds Kowloon:
@@ya city whose lights reach only to the wall is honest@@N. A city
claiming light beyond the wall had better keep those lanterns lit.
